segments.text: Monday, August 15th, 1977.
It's about quarter to four in the afternoon.
We're talking with Thomas Ramirez Ugalde.
U-L-G-A-L-D-E. U-G-A-L-D-E.
Okay, we're going to need to go over some of the stuff you and I talked about beforehand, okay, so we can get it on tape.
No, that's all right.
That's okay.
Now that we're both sitting straight.
Okay, I need to know again, you were born in what year?
I was born the 29th day of December.
29th day of December, 1890.
And where were you born?
I was born in a coal mine.
They call it Lida, Lida, something like that.
Lida?
Yeah.
And where is that?
That's in Latascoso County, Texas.
Texas, and near what big city?
Oh, San Antonio.
San Antonio, okay.
How old were you when you moved to the Rockdale area?
Well, it was about...
A little bit, but I don't remember about eight months or ten months.
Eight or ten months.
How did you learn English?
Well, I tell you, I didn't go to school.
But I learned it at the old Compras coal mine.
There was a bunch of Negroes.
They come from Alabama.
And they had little kids.
And I was a little kid, and I played with them.
That's the way I learned it.
I see.
I see.
What were your parents doing?
They were working at the coal mines.
At the coal mines.
Were the Negro children's parents working at the coal mines, too?
Yeah, there was Negro men.
They came in from Alabama, and they was working at the coal mines.
Of course, a bunch of kids, you know, we played together.
Me and Austin Garcia.
Yeah.
And Ben Torres.
Antonio Rodriguez, a bunch of kids.
And where was the compressed coal mines?
It's right where we went into Texas, you know, across the railroad, where the compressed is on this side.
I see, on the other side, on the north side of Highway 79.
Yes, sir.
Okay.
Were there very many black people that worked the mines?
Yeah, yeah.
Do any of them still live around the Rockdale area?
No, I don't think so.
They all moved away?
They all moved down in the ground.
What do you mean by that?
Died.
They died?
They died in the mines?
No, they died up in town, you see.
After the compressed mine, they worked it out, you know.
They didn't work no more.
They didn't have no more coal mines.
There was most of the colored people there moved to town.
I see.
And what year was that?
Do you remember?
I don't remember.
I was a little fellow then.
A little fellow.
Okay.
Could you describe a typical week at the mine?
You know, what you did on Monday and Tuesday and Wednesday?
Well, that's all we done.
That's all you did was mine coal?
Yeah.
That's all we done, coal.
You were telling me earlier that you...
went down in the mines with your father.
Yeah.
And about how old were you?
About eight years, eight, nine years, something like that.
And why would you go down in the mines with him?
Well, just to keep company with him.

Because there was a lot of people working, you know, but still he says, if you run around out here, you might get in trouble with these kids, and you just want to go stay with me down in the coal mine.
Were there many other children your age down there?
Oh, yes.
Mexican and college.
I see.
And how old were you when you yourself started mining?
Myself?
Yeah, right.
When I started working?
For the mines.
Huh?
Yeah, when you started coal mining yourself.
Oh, well, I don't know.
I was about, let's see, about 14.
About 14.
Did your parents have to sign a letter to let you work?
Signed some papers, so I didn't know.
Okay.
And when you were 14, were you working at the Vogel mine?
Vogel's mine, yeah.
What time of the day would you go down into the mine?
Well, it was...
They had steps going in the coal mine.
And the... Willie Helson, his father, he opened it.
They had a little door, you know, with a lock to keep people from going in there in the night and do damage down in the mine, you see?
Right.
And he opened it up about 6 o'clock in the morning, then we...
Some people go down early, some of them went down a little late.
I see.
So the miners had pretty much free reign as to when they could go down and when they could come up?
Yeah.
I see.
What time did you usually go down?
Well, we usually go down about 6.30.
The people that decode for some mule drivers and the truck man, they all started at 7 o'clock.
I see.
And how long would they work during the day?
They worked, I think, until 6.
Until 6?
I think they were working 10 hours.
10 hours a day?
Yeah.
Did they have an hour off for lunch?
Yeah.
I see.
Did you take your lunch down with you, or did you come up at lunch?
Well, a lot of people take their lunch with them, a lot of them.
And some of them were the ladies.
The man that had a wife, they'd take it out to the cold, while the chef was, you know, and put it in the elevator.
At 12 o'clock, they let all the lunch down.
What was usually in a lunch?
What kind of lunch did you eat?
Well, we ate just potatoes and bacon, the things like that.
And then in the afternoon, what time would you come up out of the coal mine?
Well, the mentors, they could come out any time.
Or you could go down any time they wanted you.
And you were telling me earlier, how many...
coal cars a day did you mine using?
Well, I'll tell you.
Here at this coal mine, I was not very much of a hand, but I could dig six, five, six, seven, eight cars of coal.
And how much were you paid per car?
Twenty cents.
Twenty cents?
Did that rate ever go up or down?
Oh, yeah.
In the summertime, they paid 25 cents.
And why was that?
Well, you see, they want the people, they had more orders for coal, and they want the people to work more.
And they didn't want the people to get out and go to the cotton field.
That's why they get paid 25, I mean 5 cents more on each car.
And that was during the summertime?
Yes.
I see.
How much would you get paid for picking cotton?
Well...
I don't remember exactly.
But 25 cents a coal car was more than you would get picking cotton?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Of course, now you take some good hands and know how to pick cotton, well, they picked a lot of cotton.
And I think they was getting about, I don't know, 50 cents per hundred, something like that.
50 cents per hundred pounds of cotton?
Okay.
What kind of machinery was there around the mines?
Well, the kind of machine they had, there was all of them steam engines, all of them.
That's what they did.
Now, to pull the, to bring the coal to the shaft, they used mules.
Inside the mine?
Inside the mine, yes.
And they would put the...
The coal where?
I mean, the coal car.
After the mule pulled it to the shaft, where would it go?
Then they put it in the elevator.
We call them cages.
Cages.
Yeah.
But they put them in the elevator and bring them to the top and dump it.
And the triple, you know, and they had a chute.
A chute.
And where would that chute go to?
Into the railroad car.
Railroad car.
Okay.
What kind of tools did you use when you were mining?
Pick and shovel, that's all he used.
That's all.
One thing I've been unclear about, Tomas, and that is, you had a straight shaft with an elevator, or a cage, as you call it.
Yeah.
And then you had one main tunnel.
Yeah.
And then you had offshoots, or little rooms, off the tunnel.
Yeah, rooms, entries.
Right.
Were there cave-ins?
Were there very many cave-ins?
Well, some of them were cave-ins, but most of them had chambers.
But for the vein of the coal...
It was about seven feet and a half, eight feet.
You know, we didn't take all the coal off.
That will hold the dirt, you know.
Leaving some of the coal would hold the dirt in place.
Did the miners put the timbers up or did somebody else come in?
No, we had to put them up because we'd get paid 25 cents for each.
For cap, cross piece, like this, you know.
This is a cross piece and this is a prop.
two props, one prop here, one prop there, and a cross bead.
Then they put some, what they call leggings.
Leggings?
They have about, some of them was three inches in diameter, some of them less, and some of them a little more.
And we put them like that, you know, to keep the place from caving.
So, and you got paid for doing that also?
Oh yeah, yeah.
25 cents for each set of timbers.
25 cents for each set of timbers?
Well, did that pay more than digging coal?
Well,
You see, you had to put up a set of timbers about every five feet.
So you just put up one set a day.
I see.
So you would get paid for maybe perhaps six car loads a day plus one set of timber.
Yes.
Okay, so that was seven times 25.
Pogo, Pogo.
Who was your boss down in the mines?
Mr. Lawrence.
Mr. Lawrence?
Lawrence.
Did he go down in the mine?
What was his name?
I think he was Gus Lawrence.
Gus Lawrence?
Yeah.
This Lawrence, he was the boss.
He was the boss one time, you know.
But then Willie Elson, his brother, named Frank Elson, he was the boss then.
You know, he got maybe a little hole or something.
He stayed on top.
Okay.
Was there any boss down below in the mines?
Just one.
Just one?
Just one, yeah.
And what was his function?
What did he... Just look at the places, and when you break through from one place into another, he'd go ahead and mark you another place.
Would he tell you where...
not to go and where to go?
No, he never said that.
Was he concerned with the safety of the miners at all?
Yeah.
How would he be concerned with safety?
Well, the safety was because, you see, there was not too many places in the coal mine caved in.
That was the safety.
I see.
There were not very many caved in?
No, no.
Only when they pull the pillars, what they call the pillars, it's from one entry or room into another.
And while the tunnel goes in, another tunnel back here, what they call pulling pillars, bring the whole thing, dig the whole thing out and set a bunch of props.
I see.
That's how come there's a lot of caves over there and holes.
Have you noticed it, buddy?
Well, them is why they pull the pillars out of the coal mine.
They call them pillars.
Well, they wouldn't pull the pillars out until they put the timber in.
Right.
They put the timber in.
Yeah, as you pull, as you be digging, you set your property.
And you could tell it about that far apart, you know, from the coal, about that far apart, three or four feet, you know, you put your property.
I see.
Okay.
And they had a track man, too, in the coal mine.
A track man.
And what did he do?
He laid a track for the coal miners.
Do you remember how much he was paid?
He was paid about $2 a day.
$2 a day.
Was there anybody that took care of the mules down there, a mule driver?
No.
Well, how did the mules pull the cars from the roof?
We had to drive them.
You had to drive the mules yourself.
I see.
We had a lamp cap and a lamp, a carbide lamp.
The question was oil lamps.
But then they got the carbide lamps along about 1912.
About 1912 is when the carbide lamps came in?
Yeah.
And then, you see, that gives you a lot of light to drive your mule with four, five cars, maybe six, according to how many places they go down a little or go up, you know?
Ah, yeah, I see.
And then that's all they could pull.
So you filled up one car?
And then hitched it onto a mule and took it to the cage.
Yeah.
And then your car went up the cage.
And they had a place with some empty cars.
Down underneath the mine?
Yeah.
Okay.
All right.
Now, how did you keep track of your cars?
Well, they had a number, you see, where all the coal diggers had a number.
They had a washer, you know?
Brass washer?
No, iron washer.
Iron washer.
But they had a stamp, you know.
They had a...

from one two three four five and your number was 12 or one or two whatever your number was then they find out that that's the way to find out how many cars of coal you dig a day I see you see on top of the temple there was a man dump the coal pull the the car out of the elevator and dump it and then when he dumps it he's down there and got got to check out and they had a
a board with a lot of nails, and they put your watch in there, and it was your check number.
There was no cars getting lost that way.
No cars got lost?
No.
They never miscounted your cars?
Oh, sure, they counted them right, too.
That's good.
Were you ever injured in the mines?
Huh?
Were you ever injured?
Did you ever have an accident?
No.
Did any of your friends ever have an accident?
No, not that I know of.
Well, what about when one of your family was sick?
How did you take care of them?
Well, I'll tell you.
When the family gets sick, now here's the way they had it.
Each coal mine had maybe a doctor or two from town.
And every person that was working in the coal mine, if he was single, he paid 25 cents every two weeks for the doctor to come and see him.
And the married man, they had family that paid 50 cents every two weeks.
And that's the way we had the doctor.
Anytime we'd get sick, something happened to the family or the children, they called the doctor, the phone of the doctor, and he'd go over there.
You didn't have to pay any extra?
No, sir.
We already was paying him 25 cents, single man, every two weeks, and 50 cents a family man.
When did you get married?
I got married in 1914.
And you got married at the mine site?
Huh?
Were you married at one of the mines?
Or did you get married in town?
No, I got married in town.
I see.
The guest of peace married me.
His name was Ed Gunn.
Ed Gunn?
Ed Gunn.
I think he died maybe two or three years ago.
I see.
Well, did you have a big party after you were married?
No.
Some of them had them, but some of them didn't.
Well, but you took your wife back to the mine camp?
Oh yeah, that's where we lived.
You met her at the mines?
Yeah, at the dances, that's where we met.
At the dances, I see.
Yeah, you see they had a big platform to give a dance.
Which mine was this?
Most of the coal mines had a platform.
where they put up, where they celebrate the holidays.
That is the 5th of May and the 16th of September.
That's the holidays for the Mexican people.
Well, did you meet your wife at the same camp where you were?
Yeah.
Okay.
Back in 1914, do you remember which coal company you were working for?
I was working for the Vogels.
Vogels?
Uh-huh.
And which mine area was that?
Was that the one we were looking at today?
No.
No, the one back in there, we didn't get to go to the coal mine.
Over by the, near the brick factory?
Yeah.
That one?
Okay.
Did you ever sing when you were down in the mines?
Huh?
Did you ever sing songs while you were down in the mines?
Oh, yeah.
What kind of songs did you sing?
Well, the same thing, you know, I'd sing, you'd sing by yourself, because you'd be in your own place.
Can you remember one of those songs?
You can't?
No.
Well, when you came out of the mines in the afternoon, what did you do?
Took a bath.
Took a bath.
Took a bath, eat a little supper, and go play ballroom.
Okay.
Did each house have a bathtub?
No, they were different.
You see, we took a bath in that tub.
And where?
In one of the ordinary tubs.
Ordinary tubs?
Yeah, we didn't have no water out there.
We paid 25 cents.
At first we used to pay 25 cents a barrel of water.
25 cents a barrel?
Yeah.
I see.
And so you'd have several people...
taking baths in one bathtub, right?
Yeah, one, just one, each one in the house, because each family had a house.
Each family had a house, and there was one tub per house.
Yeah.
Okay.
And of course, we had to buy the tub, and not the same tub that we used, that the ladies used to wash the man's clothes and wash her clothes or the children's clothes.
I see.
Now, you understand that?
Right, so you washed clothes and your body in the same bathtub.
Okay.
All right.
You said you played ball after?
Yeah, we'd get out and play ball too.
Baseball?
Yeah.
What position did you play?
Oh, I played first base, shortstop, center field.
Did you have several teams per mining camp?
Oh, just one, just one.
Just one?
Just one team, in fact.
Of course, the other coal mines, they had the same team, and on the Sunday, well, that's what we do.
We go up there and play ball.
Either team goes to...
Next coal mine or the island come and play with the rest of them.
That's the way we played ball.
I see.
Did all the family come and watch?
No.
It was just for the men?
Nothing but men, that's all.
Family stayed in the island.
We was funny, though.
We all funny, though.
It ain't like now, see?
Now, a married man at that time, our wives stayed home.
I see.
Did you...
Did you drink beer while you played ball?
No.
So you went dancing on Saturday night and played baseball on Sunday?
Yeah.
That's generally what happened?
Sometimes, you know, we'd have a dance.
Sometimes I'd go two, three weeks and all that.
Nice.
And when your wife had a baby, the doctor would come out from town?
Yeah.
Would he charge you any extra?
No, sir.
Did you get along with the Vogels and the Lawrences?
Oh, yeah.
You see, they stayed on their house.
And it was different.
They didn't go out and see the workmen or anything like that.
They didn't risk nobody.
They stayed right in their house and raised children.
And your people stayed...
Same way.
Of course...
And at that time, well, the neighbors, you know, sometimes they go and visit one each other.
Not too much.
Now you can't hardly keep a wife at home.
I've been single 30 years.
30 years?
Yes.
Let me ask you something, Tomas.
Did you vote ever in any of the Rockville elections?
I only voted twice, that's all.
When was that?
That was last year.
And...
Do you remember World War I?
Oh, yeah.
How did it affect your life in the mines?
Well, I'll tell you, I didn't go to the war because I had two children.
In the First World War, I had a Noverta girl and a boy named Benino.
He's in San Antonio.
Now, I had them two children.
That's the reason I didn't go to the war.
I see.
Well, did the mining pick up during the war?
Yeah, yeah.
Did you get paid any more money during the war?
Well, we get a little more money and the workforce later stayed.
What about, did the Ku Klux Klan ever come through this area?
No.
Not that I know.
All right, all right.
And you were telling me earlier that you left the Vogel mines in 1925?
No, the Texas, I mean the Recluta, where we was.
La Recluta.
Yeah, La Recluta.
When did you come to the La Recluta?
Well, I came in there from Big Dump in 1924.
I see.
When did you leave the Vogel mine first?
I left the Vogel coal mine in 1917, and I didn't come back until, no, 1916, I think it was.
I didn't come back until 19...
18, I think.
What did you do for those two years?
I went to pick cotton one year and then cut wood out in Christmas Texas.
That's where my second child was born.
When did you go to work for Big Lump?
I went to work at Big Lump in 1900 and I guess 1980.
I see.
And you worked there until 1924?
Yeah.
When you went back to the La Recluta?
La Recluta, yeah.
Okay.
Why did you leave the mines the first time?
When I left, I went to work at another coal mine.
I see.
Why would you leave the first mine?
Huh?
Why would you leave the first mine?
Well, I just feel like going to another place.
Did they pay better over at the other place?
No.
Was there better living conditions, maybe?
No, the same, but, you know, you get tired of staying in one place and you move to another place.
I see.
As long as you didn't owe the company nothing, you're free to go anywhere.
Did you ever owe the company anything?
No.
You always kept clear credit.
Yeah.
Like I do here in Rockdale.
I got credit at the state bank since 1922.
I see.
So every two weeks when you got paid, you always got a little bit of cash?
Oh, yeah.
I see.
How did that depression affect you?
Well... Did you quit the mines during the depression, or did you quit earlier?
No.
Let's see, when the depression time comes, I was 19...
Then I went to, in that same year, I went to pick cotton for a fellow by the name of Albert Tinneman.
He lives up here on this street.
Albert?
Albert Tinneman.
It's the German people.
I see.
Did you ever work for the Texas Coal Company?
Yeah.
You did?
Do you remember what years?
Well, it was 19, I think, the year that I worked for the Texas Gold Company.
I think it was 1911.
Yes.
Was there ever a union movement in the mines?
No.
Do you know why there wasn't?
No.
Do you like unions?
Well, I don't know nothing about the year.
So the people...
from up in the north.
Yeah, they use a unit, but that's a hard coal, what you call it, stone coal.
That's a hard coal.
Now this coal and this lignite, you take it out today and let a lump that big, or as big as my head, let it lay out in the sun in two days, that's nothing but slack, what we call it.
It breaks all the pieces.
For rain, it breaks all the pieces.
Did you ever use lignite for fuel?
Yeah, in the house.
In the house, you did?
Yeah, for heating.
Now, they didn't charge us for that.
We'd go to the mine and get it out of the railroad cars and bring it home.
They never did charge us for that.
I see.
What kind of materials did you get at the commissary?
I mean, what?
Grocers.
Yeah.
Well, just everything you, 10 goods, all kinds, everything you wanted.
And so on, they had bacon, lard, beans.
And how would you purchase these, these goods?
Well, they put it down in the book.
Put it down in the book.
Whatever you get, if you get two hours, the gross is 25 cents for this and 30 or 40 cents for this other.
And it's all rolled down on the page.
So when the week comes on the Friday, they figure out how much had you or
taken out of the store, how much was you bought.
And then payday next, and the Saturday was a payday, where they'll take it all, take all out of your wages.
They said if you made $15, well, they'd take it out of the $15 if you only had $10 gross.
That was according to the family what you had.
Where'd you buy your clothes?
Well, we'd come down and buy them.
How did you get to town?
Walk.
You'd walk?
Yeah.
About how many miles was that?
Oh, it was a while ago.
About two, three miles, maybe four.
Yeah.
You told me earlier that you were able to purchase a Model T. Yeah.
When did you do that?
Oh, that was in 1900 and, let's see, about 1930.
Because the Model T was a gift to me.
It was given to you.
Yeah, they gave it to a fella out in the country, here at the Whirly Mine.
He had a model to you, and he didn't know how to fix it.
So when I was at Big Lump, a fella by the name of Harry Steinberg, he was the pit boss of the mine at Big Lump.
And many of them got along pretty good, and I was running some steam pumps to pump the water out of the coal mine.
And they fixed the cars for the company.
And that was Mr. Henemeyer was one of the owners, I think, and E.B.
Phillips was the other owner.
Now, didn't E.B.
Phillips own the Texas mine, the Texas coal company?
I think E.B.
Phillips, I think.
I think he had a part of the coal mine in Bigelow.
And I think he did have part of Texas.
I'm sorry, I interrupted you.
Nate, you learned how to work on Model Ts?
Yeah.
Yeah, that's part of the law in me, you know.
I have to get through puppet.
I have to get through puppet while he says, Thomas, you want to learn how to fix this car?
I said, yeah, glad to.
So I'll tell you the truth.
I learned how to fix a T-model, but I didn't run it.
I was afraid I'd break it or do something to it, and I didn't run it.
So he told me a way.
He says, Thomas, you fix them, and I help you fix them, and we both work on it.
He says, go ahead and dry one.
If you break it, we'll fix it up again.
So that's the way I learned how to fix a T-model before I could dry it.
So when this man had this T-model, he didn't have no use for it.
Well, he gave it to me.
For no money?
For no money.
But in a good shape.
But he is some man with, you know.
Did you ever get around to driving it?
Well, sure.
I drove it from the Corpus Christi with all my family.
Corpus Christi?
Yeah.
It's big cotton out there.
Chopped cotton.
What year?
Yeah, vegetables.
What year was that?
Do you remember?
Yes, sir.
The interview is continued on the other side of the table.
